&lt;p&gt;Today I learned about:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;üîπ Instance Variables/ Static Variables&lt;br&gt;
üîπ Difference between Instance and Static Variables&lt;br&gt;
üîπ How memory behaves with static&lt;br&gt;
üîπ Introduction to Operators in Java&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This concept helped me understand how data can be shared across all objects in Java üî•&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;üìå What is a Static Variable?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A static variable belongs to the class, not to the object.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;üëâ It is common for all objects.&lt;br&gt;
üëâ Only one copy is created in memory.&lt;br&gt;
üëâ It is shared across every object of that class.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;üß† Instance Variable vs Static Variable&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Instance Variable---------- Static Variable&lt;br&gt;
Belongs to object---------- Belongs to class&lt;br&gt;
Separate copy for each object---Single copy shared by all&lt;br&gt;
Created inside heap with object Created once in class memory&lt;br&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;üè´ Example ‚Äì School Marks Program&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Let‚Äôs understand using your example.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class="highlight js-code-highlight"&gt;
&lt;pre class="highlight plaintext"&gt;&lt;code&gt;package java_module_1;

public class School_Vikas {

    // Instance variables
    int tam_mark;
    int eng_mark;

    // Static variable
    static String School_Name = "Vikas School";

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        School_Vikas rajiv = new School_Vikas();
        rajiv.tam_mark = 60;
        rajiv.eng_mark = 50;

        System.out.println("Rajiv's Tamil mark is " + rajiv.tam_mark);
        System.out.println("Rajiv's English mark is " + rajiv.eng_mark);

        // Calling static variable
        System.out.println("School Name " + School_Vikas.School_Name);

        // We can also call directly inside same class
        System.out.println(School_Name);

        School_Vikas kumar = new School_Vikas();
        kumar.tam_mark = 55;
        kumar.eng_mark = 45;

        System.out.println("Kumar's Tamil mark is " + kumar.tam_mark);
        System.out.println("Kumar's English mark is " + kumar.eng_mark);
    }
}
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;/div&gt;



&lt;p&gt;üîç What Happens Here?&lt;br&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;‚úÖ Instance Variables&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;
int tam_mark;&lt;br&gt;
int eng_mark;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Each object gets its own copy.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;rajiv has separate marks&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;kumar has separate marks&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Memory in Heap:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;rajiv ‚Üí tam_mark = 60&lt;br&gt;
         eng_mark = 50&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;kumar ‚Üí tam_mark = 55&lt;br&gt;
         eng_mark = 45&lt;br&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;‚úÖ Static Variable&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;
static String School_Name = "Vikas School";&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Only ONE copy is created.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Both objects share the same school name.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Memory:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Class Area:&lt;br&gt;
School_Name = "Vikas School"&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Even if we create 100 students,&lt;br&gt;
School_Name remains one common value.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;üìå How to Access Static Variable&lt;br&gt;
‚úî Using Class Name (Recommended)&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class="highlight js-code-highlight"&gt;
&lt;pre class="highlight plaintext"&gt;&lt;code&gt;School_Vikas.School_Name
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;/div&gt;



&lt;p&gt;‚úî Directly inside same class&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class="highlight js-code-highlight"&gt;
&lt;pre class="highlight plaintext"&gt;&lt;code&gt;System.out.println(School_Name);
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;/div&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;üß† Important Rule&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Static variable:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Is created when class is loaded&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Does NOT require object creation&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Is stored in class memory (Method Area)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;üî• Why Do We Use Static?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We use static when:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;‚úî Value is common for all objects&lt;br&gt;
‚úî Data should not change per object&lt;br&gt;
‚úî Utility or shared configuration&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Example:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;School Name&lt;br&gt;
College Code&lt;br&gt;
Company Name&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Interest Rate (bank example)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;‚ûï Introduction to Operators in Java&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;An operator is a special symbol used to perform operations.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Example:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt; -  *  /  %
&lt;strong&gt;üìö Types of Operators&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;1Ô∏è‚É£ Assignment Operator&lt;/strong&gt;
=&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Example:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;int a = 10;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;2Ô∏è‚É£ Arithmetic Operators&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt; -  *  /  %&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Example:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;int total = 10 + 5;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;3Ô∏è‚É£ Unary Operators&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;
++  --&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Example:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;int a = 5;&lt;br&gt;
a++;   // Increment&lt;br&gt;
a--;   // Decrement&lt;br&gt;
Types:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Post Increment ‚Üí a++&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Pre Increment ‚Üí ++a&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Post Decrement ‚Üí a--&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Pre Decrement ‚Üí --a&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;4Ô∏è‚É£ Relational Operators&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;
==  !=  &amp;lt;  &amp;gt;  &amp;lt;=  &amp;gt;=&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Used for comparison.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;5Ô∏è‚É£ Conditional Operators&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&amp;amp;&amp;amp;  || &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;amp;&amp;amp; ‚Üí AND&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;|| ‚Üí OR&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;üéØ Key Takeaways ‚Äì Day 5&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;‚úî Static variable is shared by all objects&lt;br&gt;
‚úî Instance variable belongs to each object&lt;br&gt;
‚úî Static can be accessed using class name&lt;br&gt;
‚úî Only one copy of static exists in memory&lt;br&gt;
‚úî Operators help perform calculations and comparisons&lt;/p&gt;

